## Task 1: Sign in to AWS Management Console

## Task 2: Setup Visual Studio Code

In this task, we are going to setup Visual Studio Code for running our Terraform files.

1. Open the visual studio code.  
2.  If you have already installed and using Visual studio code, open a new window.  
3. A new window will open a new file and release notes page (only if you have installed or updated Visual Studio Code recently). Close the Release notes tab.  
4. Open Terminal by selecting View from the Menu bar and choose Terminal.   
5.  It may take up to 2 minutes to open the terminal window.

![][image1]

6. Once the terminal is ready, let us navigate to the Desktop.  
7. cd Desktop  
7. Create a new folder by running the below command.  
8. mkdir task\_10119\_lambda  
8. Change your present working directory to use the newly created folder by running the below command:  
9. cd task\_10119\_lambda  
9. Get the location of the present working directory by running the below command:  
10. pwd  
10.  Note down the location, as you will open the same in the next steps.  
11.  Now click on the first icon Explorer present on the left sidebar.  
12.  Click on the button called Open folder and navigate to the location of folder task\_10119\_lambda  
13.  (Optional) Click on Authorize button for allowing Visual Studio Code to use the task\_10119\_lambda folder. This will only be asked when you have been using Visual Studio code for a while as you are allowing a new folder to be accessed by VSC.  
14.  Visual Studio Code is now ready to use.

## Task 3: Create a variables file

In this task, you will create variable files where you will declare all the global variables with a short description and a default value.

1. To create a variable file, expand the folder task\_10119\_lambda and click on the New File icon to add the file.  
2. Name the file as variables.tf and press Enter to save it.  
3. Note: Don't change the location of the new file, keep it default, i.e. inside the task\_10119\_lambda folder.  
4.  Paste the below contents in variables.tf file.

| variable "access\_key" {     description \= "Access key to AWS console" } variable "secret\_key" {     description \= "Secret key to AWS console" } variable "region" {     description \= "AWS region" } |
| :---- |

![][image2]

5. In the above content, you are declaring a variable called, access\_key, secret\_key, and region with a short description of all 3\.  
6. After pasting the above contents, save the file by pressing ctrl \+ S.  
7. Now expand the folder task\_10119\_lambda and click on the New File icon to add the file.  
8. Name the file as terraform.tfvars and press Enter to save it.  
9. Paste the below content into the terraform.tfvars file.

| region \= "us-east-1" access\_key \= "\<YOUR\_ACCESS\_KEY\>" secret\_key \= "\<YOUR\_SECRET\_KEY\>" |
| :---- |

10.   
    In the above code, you are defining the dynamic values of variables declared earlier.  
11. Replace the values of access\_key and secret\_key by copying from the lab page.  
12. After replacing the values of access\_key and secret\_key, save the file by pressing Ctrl \+ S.

![][image3]

## Task 4: Create source and destination S3 buckets in the main.tf file

In this task, you will create a main.tf file where you will add details of the provider and resources. Also, we will create two S3 buckets i.e. source and destination buckets.

1. To create a main.tf file, expand the folder task\_10119\_lambda and click on the New File icon to add the file.  
2. Name the file as main.tf and press Enter to save it.  
3. Paste the below content into the main.tf file.

| \# CONFIGURATION AND PARAMETERS provider "aws" {     region     \= "${var.region}"     access\_key \= "${var.access\_key}"     secret\_key \= "${var.secret\_key}" } |
| :---- |

      4\.   Now we will create two S3 buckets, one for the source bucket and another for the destination bucket. Paste the below code in the main.tf file.

| \#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\# Creating a Random String \#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\# resource "random\_string" "random" {   length \= 6   special \= false   upper \= false } \#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\# Creating an S3 source Bucket \#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\# resource "aws\_s3\_bucket" "sourcebucket" {   bucket \= "sourcebucket-${random\_string.random.result}"   force\_destroy \= true } \#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\# Creating an S3 destination Bucket \#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\# resource "aws\_s3\_bucket" "destinationbucket" {   bucket \= "destinationbucket-${random\_string.random.result}"   force\_destroy \= true } |
| :---- |

      5\. The provided code snippet generates a random string to ensure unique names for both the source and destination AWS S3 buckets. Then, it utilizes the "aws\_s3\_bucket" resource to create these buckets, appending the generated random string to their names. Additionally, the "force\_destroy" parameter is set to true, allowing the buckets to be forcibly deleted if needed. 

![][image4]

## Task 5: Create a lambda function in the main.tf file

In this task, we are going to create a lambda function in the main.tf file by providing the required configurations like name, runtime, IAM role, and other details.

     1\. Firstly you will download [index.zip](https://labresources.whizlabs.com/65edbeffa9757a31724e3b4b64ebf15d/index.zip) and upload it locally to your folder task\_10119\_lambda.

     2\. Name the zip file as index.zip.

           ![][image5]

     3\. To create a lambda function, paste the following contents in the main.tf file:

     4\. In the role, replace the \<ACCOUNT\_ID\> with your account\_id of the AWS Account.

| resource "aws\_lambda\_function" "test\_lambda" {   filename      \= "index.zip"   function\_name \= "Whizlabsfunc"   role          \= "arn:aws:iam::\<ACCOUNT\_ID\>:role/Lambda\_role"   handler       \= "index.handler"   runtime \= "nodejs16.x" } |
| :---- |

    5\. Save the file by pressing Ctrl \+ S. 

## Task 6: Create a lambda trigger in the main.tf file

In this task we are going to create a lambda trigger for S3. Whenever the user uploads any object in the source bucket , it will automatically trigger the lambda function and the object will be copied in the destination bucket.

1. In the **main.tf** file, paste the following code :

| resource "aws\_s3\_bucket\_notification" "aws-lambda-trigger" {   bucket \= aws\_s3\_bucket.sourcebucket.id   lambda\_function {     lambda\_function\_arn \= aws\_lambda\_function.test\_lambda.arn     events   \= \["s3:ObjectCreated:\*"\]   } } |
| :---- |

2.   
   In the above code, we have set up an AWS S3 bucket notification for an S3 bucket named "sourcebucket". The notification is configured to trigger an AWS Lambda function, "test\_lambda," whenever an object is created in the "sourcebucket". The Lambda function is associated with the event "s3:ObjectCreated: \*," which means it will be executed whenever a new object is added to the specified S3 bucket.  
3. To add the permissions for the Lambda function to invoke trigger, paste the following code in the main.tf file:

| resource "aws\_lambda\_permission" "test" {   statement\_id  \= "AllowS3Invoke"   action        \= "lambda:InvokeFunction"   function\_name \= aws\_lambda\_function.test\_lambda.function\_name   principal     \= "s3.amazonaws.com"   source\_arn    \= "arn:aws:s3:::${aws\_s3\_bucket.sourcebucket.id}" } |
| :---- |

      4\. The provided Terraform code creates an access permission configuration between an AWS Lambda function and an S3 bucket. It enables the specified S3 bucket to invoke (trigger) the  specified Lambda function by granting the "lambda:InvokeFunction" action to the S3 bucket's principal. The permission allows the Lambda function to be triggered whenever specific events, like object creations, occur in the S3 bucket.

## Task 7: Create an output file

In this task, you will create an output.tf file where you will add details of the provider and resources.

1. To create an output.tf file, expand the folder task\_10119\_lambda and ,click on the New File icon to add the file.  
2. Name the file as output.tf and press Enter to save it.  
3. Paste the below content into the output.tf file. In the below code, we will extract the lambda arn. 

| output "lambda\_arn" {  value \= "${aws\_lambda\_function.test\_lambda.arn}" } |
| :---- |

## Task 8: Confirm the installation of Terraform by checking the version

1. In the Visual Studio Code, open Terminal by selecting View from the Menu bar and choose Terminal.  
2. If you are not in the newly created folder change your present working directory by running the below command.  
   cd task\_10119\_lambda  
3. To confirm the installation of Terraform, run the below command to check the version:  
4. terraform version

     4\. If you are getting output as command not found: terraform, this means that terraform is not installed on your system, To install terraform follow the official guide link provided in the Prerequisite section above.

## Task 9: Apply terraform configurations

1. Initialize Terraform by running the below command,  
   terraform init  
   Note: terraform init will check for all the plugin dependencies and download them if required, this will be used for creating a deployment plan.  
   ![][image7]  
2. To generate the action plans run the below command,

3. terraform plan

  ![][image8]

     3\. To create all the resources declared in main.tf configuration file, run the below command,

terraform apply

4. Approve the creation of all the resources by entering yes.  
* Note: This process will take around 5-10 minutes. 

![][image9]

5. Idâ€™s of all the resources created by terraform will be visible there.

## Task 10: Check the resources in the AWS Console

1. Navigate to the Services menu at the top. Click on S3 in the Storage section.  
2. You can see that two buckets will be created. One with the name sourcebucket-xxxxx and the other with the name destinationbucket-xxxxxx. Copy both the bucket names. 

![][image10]

      3\.  Go to the Services menu and click on Lambda under Compute section. Make sure you are in the US East (N. Virginia) region.

     4\. You can view one Lambda function created with the name Whizlabsfunc.

![][image11]

    5\. Click on the function and scroll down to the Code Area. Paste the names of the source bucket and destination bucket in Lines 4 & 5\.

![][image12]

     6\. Click on Deploy button to save the updated code. 

## Task 11: Test the Lambda Function

Note: If you use AWS CLI to find resources by security group, EC2 instances are attached to EC2 security groups, while RDS instances are attached to their own security groups. RDS security groups often allow inbound access from an EC2 security group, so use the EC2 security group when filtering instances and the RDS security group when filtering DBs.

1. Navigate to the Services menu at the top. Click on S3 in the Storage section. Make sure you are in the US East (N. Virginia) region.

       2\. Click on the source bucket and Click on Upload button.

![][image13]

     3\.  Click on Add files button and Browse for your local image or Download this [image](https://labresources.whizlabs.com/65edbeffa9757a31724e3b4b64ebf15d/smiley_00_04.jpg).

     4\.  Click on the Upload button.

      5\. Navigate back to the buckets and click on the destination bucket. You will notice that an object is already there, which is identical to the one you uploaded to the source bucket.

### Do you know ?

AWS Lambda bills execution time in increments of 100 milliseconds. This granular billing ensures that you are charged only for the precise amount of compute time used.

2. Run the below command to delete all the resources. Enter yes to confirm the deletion.   
3. terraform destroy
